<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1919-05-16T13:29:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1919-05-16T13:29:00-05:00" n="24" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d24">
                            <note rend="inline" type="source">837.00/1550: Telegram</note>
                            <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Gonzales</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                                        State</gloss></hi></head>
                            <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1919-05-16T13:00:00-05:29"><hi rend="italic">May 16,
                                            1919, 1 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[<hi rend="italic">Received
                                        3.35 p.m.</hi>]</dateline></opener>
                            <p>27. My May 11th, midnight. In a published address Rafael Montalvo who
                                was expected to be nominated for President by Conservative
                                convention this month announces that congressional committee is
                                working with General Crowder on electoral reform law which country
                                needs and as an elemental courtesy to General Crowder and Congress
                                he advocates postponement of presidential nominations and asks
                                friends to cease efforts for early convening of convention of
                                Conservative Party.</p>
                            <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Gonzales</hi></signed></closer>
                        </div>
                        </body></text></TEI>